I've used the `tree` command with the `/F` flag to show all files in the directory structure. The `/F` flag displays the full path of each file. This gives you a complete view of your project's file structure.

Some useful variations of the `tree` command you can use:

1. `tree /F` - Shows all files and folders (what we just used)
2. `tree /A` - Uses ASCII characters instead of extended characters
3. `tree /F /A` - Shows all files using ASCII characters
4. `tree /F /A > filelist.txt` - Saves the output to a text file

You can also specify a directory path after the command to view a specific folder's structure, for example:
```
tree /F src
```

_**Agent (mode Ask)**_

Let me help you get a cleaner tree view. Here's how to use the tree command to exclude node_modules:

```bash
tree /F /A | findstr /V "node_modules"
```

For an even cleaner view focusing on just your main project files, you might want to look at specific directories like:

```bash
tree src /F /A
```

This will show just your source code directory structure. The key project files and directories you probably care about most are:

```
src/
├───assets/
├───components/
│   ├───AlbumItem.vue
│   ├───PlaylistItem.vue
│   └───TheHeader.vue
├───router/
│   └───index.js
├───utils/
│   ├───api.js
│   ├───auth.js
│   └───cache.js
├───views/
│   ├───AccountView.vue
│   ├───HomeView.vue
│   ├───LoginView.vue
│   ├───PlaylistSingle.vue
│   └───PlaylistView.vue
├───App.vue
├───constants.js
├───firebase.js
├───main.js
└───style.scss
```

This gives you a much clearer view of your application structure without all the node_modules and other dependencies. Would you like to see any specific directory in more detail?
